<h2 id="design-breakdown---puzzles">Design breakdown - puzzles</h2>

<p>Boxes may have been made as part of a game jam, but I‚Äôd been wanted to make such a game for some time. It was borne out of a deep-seated love for ‚Äòcasual‚Äô mobile puzzle games - the kind that hook you in and keep you playing even after your commute is over.</p>

<p>Take the popular mobile game Two Dots as an example. The premise is simple - connect two or more dots of the same colour to remove them from the grid. Connecting four or more dots into a square removes all of the dots of that colour from the grid.</p>

<p>Each level has different goals - ‚Äòremove 60 blue dots‚Äô is a basic example. The traditional mobile game staples - such as lives, an overworld progression system, and three-star grading on completing a level - are all present.</p>

<p>I‚Äôve completed over 1000 levels on Two Dots, but I keep coming back because of two things.</p>

<ul>
